                <note rend="inline" type="source">123 D 811/29: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dresel</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-11-16T17:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 16, 1921—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 17—8:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>793. I today informed Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs that the American
                    Government deemed diplomatic relations might be resumed, and asked for
                    recognition provisionally as Chargé dAffaires <hi rend="italic">ad interim</hi>.
                    He replied that the German Government was ready to resume diplomatic relations
                    and that I am recognized in the capacity mentioned as from this date.<note
                        n="27" xml:id="d35fn27">Mr. Dresel’s nomination as Chargé, to date from Nov.
                        14, was confirmed by the Senate Nov. 18. He presented his letter of credence
                        as Chargé d’Affaires to the German Chancellor, acting for the Minister for
                        Foreign Affairs, Dec. 10, 1921.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dresel</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
